===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|knif}}, from late {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|cnīf}}, from Old Norse {{m|non|knífr}} (compare Danish/Swedish/Norwegian {{m|sv|kniv}}), from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*knībaz}} (compare Low German {{m|nds|Knief}}, {{cog|lb|Knäip}} ‘penknife’), from {{m|gem-pro|*knīpaną}} ‘to pinch’ (compare Dutch {{m|nl|knijpen}}, Low German {{m|nds|kniepen}}, Old High German {{m|goh|gniffen}}), from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*gneibʰ-}} (compare Lithuanian {{m|lt|gnýbti}}, {{m|lt|žnýbti}} ‘to pinch’, {{m|lt|gnaibis}} ‘pinching’). Replaced Middle English {{m|enm|sax}}.

The verb ''knife'' is attested since the mid 1800s;<ref>{{R:MWO}}</ref> the variant {{m|en|knive}} is attested since 1733.<!--see entry-->

